comments.body:
For any **proper** prior $\pi$ with $E[X]<\infty$, prove:
(a) $E[Y]=E[X]$ (full symmetry of the exchange);
(b) $\int P(X\in dx)\,(E[Y\mid X=x]-x)=0$ exactly (prior-weighted switching gain is zero), justifying the interchange of expectation/conditioning via integrability (tower property hypotheses);
(c) therefore $E[Y\mid X=x]-x$ **cannot be $\ge0$ for all $x$** — it is $<0$ on a set of positive probability. This refutes 'always switch' without invoking nonlinearity of utility. A numerical instance (verified in this review) has the conditional gain positive for small $x$ but strictly negative at the largest atom, with total $0$. Provide the full proof, not the example alone.
